criptions, as the literal rendering is sufficiently clear.</note>
<note>10 <I>Ferruminata.</I> These accretions are practically always near the hearth, and would
correspond to English &ldquo;sows,&rdquo; and therefore that term has been adopted. It will be noted
that, like most modern metallurgists, Agricola offers no method for treating them. Pliny
(XXXIV, 37) describes a &ldquo;sow,&rdquo; and uses the verb <I>ferruminare</I> (to weld or solder): &ldquo;Some
say that in the furnace there are certain masses of stone which become soldered together,
and that the copper fuses around it, the mass not becoming liquid unless it is transferred
to another furnace; it thus forms a sort of knot, as it were, of the metal.&rdquo;</note>
