of these granules are placed in an earthen crucible, if it has such capacity.
For every <I>l&iacute;bra</I> of silver granules, weighed before they were sprinkled with
<p n=>450</p>
sulphur, there is weighed out also a sixth of a <I>l&iacute;bra</I> and a <I>sic&iacute;l&iacute;cus</I> of
copper, if each <I>libra</I> consists either of three-quarters of a <I>l&iacute;bra</I> of silver and
a quarter of a <I>libra</I> of copper, or of three-quarters of a <I>libra</I> and a
<I>sem&iacute;-uncia</I> of silver and a sixth of a <I>libra</I> and a <I>sem&iacute;-unc&iacute;a</I> of copper. If,
however, the silver contains five-sixths of a <I>libra</I> of silver and a sixth of a
