appear from this statement that where Agricola uses the word <I>centumpondium</I> he means the
German <I>centner.</I> On the other hand, in the previous five or six pages the expressions one-third,
five-sixths, ten-twelfths of a <I>libra</I> are used, which are even divisions of the Roman 12 <I>unciae</I>
to one <I>libra,</I> and are used where they manifestly mean divisions of 12 units. If Agricola
had in mind the German scale, and were using the <I>libra</I> for a <I>pfundt</I> of 16 <I>untzen,</I> these divisions
would amount to fractions, and would not total the <I>sicilicus</I> and <I>drachma</I> quantities given,
nor would they total any of the possibly synonymous divisions of the German <I>untzen</I> (see
also page 254).</note>
