cussion of this substance is given in the note on p. 112; and it is sufficient to state here that in
Agricola's time the metal cobalt was unknown, and the substances designated <I>cadmia</I> and
<I>cobaltum</I> were arsenical-cobalt-zinc minerals. A metal made from &ldquo;slag&rdquo; from refining,
together with &ldquo;base&rdquo; thorns, would be very impure; for the latter, according to the paragraph
on concentrates a little later on, would contain the furnace accretions, and would thus be
undoubtedly zincky. It is just possible that the term <I>kobelt</I> was used by the German smelters
at this time in the sense of an epithet&mdash;&ldquo;black devil&rdquo; (see Note 21, p. 214).</note>
<note>33 It is somewhat difficult to see exactly the meaning of base (<I>vile</I>) and precious
